T1  - Antisemitism and socialist strategy in Europe, 1880-1917: an introduction
AN  - 1973044983
AB  - This special issue focuses on the relationship between socialists and Jews across six European countries between 1880 and 1917. This was a period marked by a sustained cycle of protest in the course of which socialist parties began to draw increasingly significant support from their core constituency of the industrial working class. Over the course of this wave of contentious politics, union membership rose in Germany from tens of thousands in the 1870s to several millions by the dawn of the twentieth century while in Britain, significant sections of the ‘unrespectable’ working class—that great mass of unskilled and labouring poor—began to organize and, in the process, transformed trade unionism beyond its traditional constituency of craft workers. Many of the parties that acquired their strength from this revolt of the industrial proletariat, including the Sozialdemokratische Partei Deutschlands (SPD, Social Democratic Party of Germany), came to affiliate to the Second International, an umbrella organisation formed in 1889 to further the cause of working-class emancipation around the world. By 1914, the affiliate parties of the Second International commanded a collective membership of more than four million members and a parliamentary vote of more than twice that number. The era of collectivist socialist politics was born.
