T1  - Passive Ageism and Its Effect on Older Adults' Finances
AN  - 1750054824
AB  - The topic of ageism and finances is broad, but nuanced. There are, however, two large, obvious clusters where age and money matters intersect: As people earn income, and as they save, manage, and protect their accumulated assets. Unfortunately, ageism in the workplace is common and will rise in notoriety, as the share of the workforce ages 55 and older will increase by 38 percent from 2010 to 2020. Due to broad changes in the retirement benefit landscape, saving, managing, and protecting assets are difficult for any individual, including older adults. These retirement landscape changes thrust the responsibility further onto individuals. The issue of ageism and finances is multifaceted and complex. While there are sources of overt and active ageism, people have tried to take a less traditional and more nuanced view of ageism. They've attempted to identify how some unconscious biases and rules that the financial system operates under contribute to systemic inaction leading to ageism against older adults.
